\begin_layout Section*
Abstract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define a minimal machine—the 
\emph on
Parasite
\emph default
—that operates on relations rather than substances. It consists of a directed relation 
\begin_inset Formula $A \rightarrow B$
\end_inset

 and a third position 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 that acts on the relation itself. The third position can operate as noise or as a metastable entity. Roles 
\begin_inset Formula $(A,B,C)$
\end_inset

 are not intrinsic and may permute. A distance parameter controls the strength of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

's action. We show how this machine generates structure without conserved quantities or predefined ontology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
1. Primitive structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with a directed relation: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
A \rightarrow B
\]
\end_inset

and a third position 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 that acts on the relation: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
C \triangleright (A \rightarrow B).
\]
\end_inset

No assumption is made that 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,C$
\end_inset

 are substances. They are positions within a relational configuration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
2. Distance and coupling
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $d \ge 0$
\end_inset

 denote the distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 to the relation. Define coupling: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
k = \frac{1}{d + \epsilon}.
\]
\end_inset

As 
\begin_inset Formula $d \to \infty$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k \to 0$
\end_inset

 (negligible influence). As 
\begin_inset Formula $d \to 0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k \to \infty$
\end_inset

 (dominant influence).
\end_layout

